description:
The Chinese Language House will turn the SU into a Beijing/Taipei-style night market to celebrate Mid-Autumn Festival on Thursday, September 19 from 6-8pm. The festival is held on a full moon of the 15th day of the eighth month in the Chinese calendar, which falls on September 19 this year. Next to Chinese New Year, Mid-Autumn Festival is considered the second most important holiday tradition, and is observed by Chinese, Taiwanese, and Vietnamese. 

Making and sharing mooncakes is one of the hallmark traditions of this festival. Another big component of this celebration is an outdoor barbecue with friends and family. We plan on having many different types of traditional Chinese food (hot pot and dim sum) along with popular street food items such as bubble milk tea, and Beijing BBQ or chuanr. The Portland Orchids Bamboo Ensemble will play traditional Chinese music in the background for the duration of this event. If weather permits, we will go outside and worship the moon by reciting poetry or singing songs while eating mooncakes, another important part of this holiday.

I tried to acquire a keg set up last semester, only came through on picking up a (supacheap) co2 tank. After a ton of craigslisting I'm opting to go commercial: F. H. Steinbarts sells everything else I need.
I should point out the keg will be mad useful for liblob booch drops as well as catering various campus events (canyon day, GF stuff, whatever).

Kombucha ingredients should last the semester. I'm aiming for 3 kegged boochdrops by Spring/Fall in addition to whatever events people want me to cater. I'm also still handing out booch mothers like candy, but that's a minor outlay.

I'm also looking to get some kombucha brewing capital for a Reedie interested in brewing large sums of kombucha, in the same fashion Brewer's Guild buys capital for Reedie brewing. The equipment will be owned by Kayam and be passed down for posterity, ever brewing kombucha for Reedies.

organization: Reed Air Force Aerial Acrobatics Troupe
description: We bring you high-flying, awe-inspiring aerial acrobatics for any and all Reed events. We have performed in the past at Renn Fayre, RAW, Halloween and more, and are always trying to create new, exciting tricks and performances for the Reed community. Our troupe is open to all Reed students, alum and faculty of any skill level who are interested in performing or learning the art of aerial silks and aerial lyra.

Association for Computing Machinery is a national organization that helps bring together a community of computer science from local chapters around the world. Reed College's student chapter runs various activities related to practical and theoretical computer science.

This semester we are bringing in various speakers from the computer science community including professors from Portland State, Alumni from Twitter, Google and Square, and other Tech Startups to talk about software and connect with students.

We will be offering workshops for those curious about Software Engineering and building a semester long project which involves front end and back end development of a web application to be hosted on Reed's servers.

We will be participating in various programming competitions throughout the semester and will be hosting programming practices every Sunday.

We have multiple faculty sponsors and have faculty who attend our meetings and are trying to get off the ground running.

We want to teach people to make a variety of fermented/cured meats, along with cheese and other preserved foods. We'll get Portland celebrity butchers/chefs to lead workshops on making these fine foods. Maybe we'll even take a club field trip to Cabela's to buy a meat smoker. Top 6 us and you'll learn how to be that asshole who fills your dorm kitchen with the stench of pickled eggs and pate.

The BPR is a beloved Reed institution that provides a space for members of the community to create music and form connections. Unfortunately, the PA system - a vital element of the BPR - was stolen at the beginning of the summer. This has made it difficult for many bands to practice, and in order for the BPR to serve its unique function in the Reed community we must replace it.

The Black Student Union is a student group committed to celebrating Black American and African diasporic culture on the Reed Campus. Through monthly meetings, we provide a safe and inclusive environment where Black students can connect with students of similar backgrounds and heritages. In addition to meetings, the Black Student Union hosts discussion groups, social events, and speakers all geared towards exploring the complexities and the diversity of Black/African-American culture within the context of the  Reed community and in society at large.

La Maison Macabre. A campus wide event to celebrate mysterious aspects of the francophone world. This includes a bilingual poetry reading, an exhibit of bizarre art and film from the 18th century and a interactive history of voodoo and its practices.
We need 2 ropes to climb with, and we'll be taking 1 trip up mount Adams, 2 to Smith Rock, and one to California or Washington over Fall Break.

Friday, November 1st in Winch (7-10 PM appx), the Spanish House will be hosting "El Carnaval Hispano". We will be serving an extensive menu of food, that we  will cook ourselves from seven different, predominantly Spanish-speaking countries. We will put up booths with information from these countries, that we will later use in trivia games and raffles to give away small prizes. There will be Spanish music and dancing.  We want want to give students a chance to experience food from all over the world, to learn about the places this food comes from, and to be able to differentiate between these countries but also see what has remained similar after a long period of being colonized. We will be serving food from Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Costa Rica, Cuba, Mexico, and Spain. This event will be advertised via flyers, SB info, and the Quest. (this is for Top 40)
